[As more cases of hepatitis A virus (HAV) infection occur in more states, it remains important to develop a different paradigm of prevention. In the USA, HAV infection is no longer a disease of travelers to the developing world, eaters of contaminated foods or in males who have sex with males. These outbreaks reflect what occurs in the developing world transmission related to poor sanitation.

Because many of these disenfranchised cohorts have little access to health care and little funds to pay for the care and vaccines, it is difficult to make headway, although the San Diego county response to their outbreak did demonstrate ways to control it. It is also likely that these cohorts spend time working as food workers, and as the Florida post documents and many more media reports in various states underscore, there is substantial risk of overflow into the unsuspecting restaurant-going public. Just as the CDC is now recommending immunization for the homeless population, it is high time to consider the same for food preparers. - Mod.LL

